When opener is known to have a 4-card raise (_e.g._{thinsp} no support
double), then new suits are natural game-tries.

[#_1h_1s_2s]
=== 1H{ndash}1S{semicolon} 2S

@ bids below 3NT are natural, invitational
_ and non-forcing

@ 3NT and 4m are slam-tries with spades as trump

[%autowidth,cols="3*^,<",grid="none"]
|===
| 1H | 1S  ||
| 2S | ?   ||
|    | 2NT || natural, inv, NF, 4{times}{S}
|    | 3m  || #natural, inv, NF, 4{times}{S} & 5{times}m#
|    | 3H  || 3-card LR (NF back-preference), 4{times}{S}
|    | 3S  || five-card suit, inv
|  | !3NT! || [lavender-bg]#5{times}{S}, slam interest, FORCING#
|    | 4m  || #{thinsp}2nd-suit, slam-try, hence 5{times}{S}{thinsp}#
|    | 4H  || picture bid, 5{times}{S} & 4{times}{H}, pure hand,
              [nobr]#no control in either minor#
|    | 4S  || to play
|===

****
.Why 3m shows exactly five cards

With 4{times}{S} and a six-card minor, responder will usually treat
the hand as a single-suited with the minor, because to bid spades
first would make it impossible to introduce the minor on many auctions.
****

****
.Why 3NT is not natural

@ Responder has at least five spades to bid
_ 1S over 1H with GF values

@ If opener has four spades we have a
_ nine-card fit

@ With only three spades, opener has a singleton
_ or weak doubleton

{implies} we prefer spades to notrump

{implies} we don't need a choice-of-game 3NT
****

